text:
North on Fifth Avenue from 51st Street. Building marked X is William K. Vanderbilt Mansion. At extreme left are the twin Vanderbilt mansions. The first Church is St. Thomas's Protestant-Episcopal.
This later burned and was re-built.
1900.
Ewing Galloway, photographer.

Fifth Avenue north from 51st Street, showing Easter Sunday crowds. Two automobiles may be seen in this picture--one, in left foreground is south-bound, and is almost at N.W. corner of 51st Street. The other is north-bound, and is in right centre of picture. 1903.

Ewing Galloway, Photographer.

title: General view - 5th Avenue - Southwest.

text:
640 Fifth Avenue, at the N. W. corner of West 51st St., showing the Vanderbilt home, prior to its proposed demolition. This structure has been sold to the Astor real estate interests and who plan to erect a commercial two story structure here. It was the first of the numerous Vanderbilt houses in this area and now is the last. It was erected for Mrs. William H. Vanderbilt who became the dominant figure in society. Recognition here connoted social acceptance. General Cornelius Vanderbilt inherited it at a later date.

October 26, 1940

Robert A. Knudtsen
221 E. 31st St., N.Y.C.

Fifth Avenue, east side, south from 52nd Street (right), showing prominently the steeples being added to St. Patrick's Cathedral. This edifice was projected by Archbishop Hughs, and the cornerstone laid in 1858. It was opened in 1879. The steeples were added in 1888. On the right is the R. C. Orphan Asylum for Boys, occupying the 52nd to 51st Street frontage. It was founded in 1825 and incorporated in 1852. The present buildings were completed in 1851.

Date: 1888
Gift of Ubrock Collection
